\begin_layout Standard
To see that these conditions are in fact weaker, we can apply an easy padding
 argument.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\P=\NP$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\NE$
\end_inset

.
 We say the 
\emph on
tally encoding
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $T(L)=\{0^{x}\mid x\in L\}$
\end_inset

, where every member of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

 is represented by the tally notation of the number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since this gives us a exponential blow-up for all members of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(L)\in\NP=\P$
\end_inset

.
 The same argument rolled back gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\E$
\end_inset

.
 An equivalent argument can be applied for 
\begin_inset Formula $\EE$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\EEE$
\end_inset

 and so on.
\end_layout

